# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: client-side-prediction
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] In navigation, **dead reckoning** is the process of calculating the current position of a moving object by using a previously determined position, or fix, and incorporating estimates of speed, heading (or direction or course), and elapsed time.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] The corresponding term in biology, to describe the processes by which animals update their estimates of position or heading, is path integration.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] Advances in navigational aids that give accurate information on position, in particular satellite navigation using the Global Positioning System, have made simple dead reckoning by humans obsolete for most purposes.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] However, inertial navigation systems, which provide very accurate directional information, use dead reckoning and are very widely applied.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] Contrary to myth, the term "dead reckoning" was not originally used to abbreviate "deduced reckoning", nor is it a misspelling of the term "ded reckoning".
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] The use of "ded" or "deduced reckoning" is not known to have appeared earlier than 1931, much later in history than "dead reckoning", which appeared as early as 1613 according to the Oxford English Dictionary.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] The original intention of "dead" in the term is generally assumed to mean using a stationary object that is "dead in the water" as a basis for calculations.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] Additionally, at the time the first appearance of "dead reckoning", "ded" was considered a common spelling of "dead".
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] This potentially led to later confusion of the origin of the term.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] By analogy with their navigational use, the words *dead reckoning* are also used to mean the process of estimating the value of any variable quantity by using an earlier value and adding whatever changes have occurred in the meantime.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] Often, this usage implies that the changes are not known accurately.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] The earlier value and the changes may be measured or calculated quantities.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] While dead reckoning can give the best available information on the present position with little math or analysis, it is subject to significant errors of approximation.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] For precise positional information, both speed and direction must be accurately known at all times during travel.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] Most notably, dead reckoning does not account for directional drift during travel through a fluid medium.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] These errors tend to compound themselves over greater distances, making dead reckoning a difficult method of navigation for longer journeys.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] For example, if displacement is measured by the number of rotations of a wheel, any discrepancy between the actual and assumed traveled distance per rotation, due perhaps to slippage or surface irregularities, will be a source of error.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] As each estimate of position is relative to the previous one, errors are cumulative, or compounding, over time.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] The accuracy of dead reckoning can be increased significantly by using other, more reliable methods to get a new fix part way through the journey.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] For example, if one was navigating on land in poor visibility, then dead reckoning could be used to get close enough to the known position of a landmark to be able to see it, before walking to the landmark itself—giving a precisely known starting point—and then setting off again.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] Localizing a static sensor node is not a difficult task because attaching a Global Positioning System (GPS) device suffices the need of localization.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] But a mobile sensor node, which continuously changes its geographical location with time is difficult to localize.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] Mostly mobile sensor nodes within some particular domain for data collection can be used, *i.e*, sensor node attached to an animal within a grazing field or attached to a soldier on a battlefield.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] Within these scenarios a GPS device for each sensor node cannot be afforded.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] Some of the reasons for this include cost, size and battery drainage of constrained sensor nodes.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] To overcome this problem a limited number of reference nodes (with GPS) within a field is employed.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] These nodes continuously broadcast their locations and other nodes in proximity receive these locations and calculate their position using some mathematical technique like trilateration.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] For localization, at least three known reference locations are necessary to localize.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] Several localization algorithms based on Sequential Monte Carlo (SMC) method have been proposed in literature.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] Sometimes a node at some places receives only two known locations and hence it becomes impossible to localize.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] To overcome this problem, dead reckoning technique is used.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] With this technique a sensor node uses its previous calculated location for localization at later time intervals.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] For example, at time instant 1 if node A calculates its position as *loca_1* with the help of three known reference locations; then at time instant 2 it uses *loca_1* along with two other reference locations received from other two reference nodes.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] This not only localizes a node in less time but also localizes in positions where it is difficult to get three reference locations.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] In studies of animal navigation, dead reckoning is more commonly (though not exclusively) known as path integration.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] Animals use it to estimate their current location based on their movements from their last known location.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] Animals such as ants, rodents, and geese have been shown to track their locations continuously relative to a starting point and to return to it, an important skill for foragers with a fixed home.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] In marine navigation a "dead" reckoning plot generally does not take into account the effect of currents or wind.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] Aboard ship a dead reckoning plot is considered important in evaluating position information and planning the movement of the vessel.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] Dead reckoning begins with a known position, or fix, which is then advanced, mathematically or directly on the chart, by means of recorded heading, speed, and time.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] Speed can be determined by many methods.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] Before modern instrumentation, it was determined aboard ship using a chip log.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] More modern methods include pit log referencing engine speed (*e.g*. in rpm) against a table of total displacement (for ships) or referencing one's indicated airspeed fed by the pressure from a pitot tube.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] This measurement is converted to an equivalent airspeed based upon known atmospheric conditions and measured errors in the indicated airspeed system.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] A naval vessel uses a device called a pit sword (rodmeter), which uses two sensors on a metal rod to measure the electromagnetic variance caused by the ship moving through water.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] This change is then converted to ship's speed.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] Distance is determined by multiplying the speed and the time.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] This initial position can then be adjusted resulting in an estimated position by taking into account the current (known as set and drift in marine navigation).
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] If there is no positional information available, a new dead reckoning plot may start from an estimated position.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] In this case subsequent dead reckoning positions will have taken into account estimated set and drift.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] Dead reckoning positions are calculated at predetermined intervals, and are maintained between fixes.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] Factors including one's speed made good and the nature of heading and other course changes, and the navigator's judgment determine when dead reckoning positions are calculated.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] Before the 18th-century development of the marine chronometer by John Harrison and the lunar distance method, dead reckoning was the primary method of determining longitude available to mariners such as Christopher Columbus and John Cabot on their trans-Atlantic voyages.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] Tools such as the traverse board were developed to enable even illiterate crew members to collect the data needed for dead reckoning.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] Polynesian navigation, however, uses different wayfinding techniques.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] On 14 June, 1919, John Alcock and Arthur Brown took off from Lester's Field in St.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] They navigated across the Atlantic Ocean by dead reckoning and landed in County Galway, Ireland at 8:40 a.m. on 15 June completing the first non-stop transatlantic flight.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] On 21 May 1927 Charles Lindbergh landed in Paris, France after a successful non-stop flight from the United States in the single-engined *Spirit of St.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] As the aircraft was equipped with very basic instruments, Lindbergh used dead reckoning to navigate.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] Dead reckoning in the air is similar to dead reckoning on the sea, but slightly more complicated.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] The density of the air the aircraft moves through affects its performance as well as winds, weight, and power settings.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] The basic formula for DR is Distance = Speed x Time.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] An aircraft flying at 250 knots airspeed for 2 hours has flown 500 nautical miles through the air.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] The wind triangle is used to calculate the effects of wind on heading and airspeed to obtain a magnetic heading to steer and the speed over the ground (groundspeed).
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] Printed tables, formulae, or an E6B flight computer are used to calculate the effects of air density on aircraft rate of climb, rate of fuel burn, and airspeed.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] A course line is drawn on the aeronautical chart along with estimated positions at fixed intervals (say every half hour).
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] Visual observations of ground features are used to obtain fixes.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] By comparing the fix and the estimated position corrections are made to the aircraft's heading and groundspeed.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] Dead reckoning is on the curriculum for VFR (visual flight rules – or basic level) pilots worldwide.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] It is taught regardless of whether the aircraft has navigation aids such as GPS, ADF and VOR and is an ICAO Requirement.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] Many flying training schools will prevent a student from using electronic aids until they have mastered dead reckoning.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] Inertial navigation systems (INSes), which are nearly universal on more advanced aircraft, use dead reckoning internally.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] The INS provides reliable navigation capability under virtually any conditions, without the need for external navigation references, although it is still prone to slight errors.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] The first automotive navigation systems pre-dated the availability of GPS and relied instead on dead reckoning-based systems.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] Honda's Electro Gyrocator, launched in 1981, was the first commercially available car navigation system.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] It used inertial navigation systems, which tracked the distance traveled, the start point, and direction headed.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] Dead reckoning is today implemented in some high-end automotive navigation systems in order to overcome the limitations of GPS/GNSS technology alone.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] Satellite microwave signals are unavailable in parking garages and tunnels, and often severely degraded in urban canyons and near trees due to blocked lines of sight to the satellites or multipath propagation.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] In a dead-reckoning navigation system, the car is equipped with sensors that know the wheel circumference and record wheel rotations and steering direction.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] These sensors are often already present in cars for other purposes (anti-lock braking system, electronic stability control) and can be read by the navigation system from the controller-area network bus.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] The navigation system then uses a Kalman filter to integrate the always-available sensor data with the accurate but occasionally unavailable position information from the satellite data into a combined position fix.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] Dead reckoning is utilized in some robotic applications.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] It is usually used to reduce the need for sensing technology, such as ultrasonic sensors, GPS, or placement of some linear and rotary encoders, in an autonomous robot, thus greatly reducing cost and complexity at the expense of performance and repeatability.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] The proper utilization of dead reckoning in this sense would be to supply a known percentage of electrical power or hydraulic pressure to the robot's drive motors over a given amount of time from a general starting point.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] Dead reckoning is not totally accurate, which can lead to errors in distance estimates ranging from a few millimeters (in CNC machining) to kilometers (in UAVs), based upon the duration of the run, the speed of the robot, the length of the run, and several other factors.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] With the increased sensor offering in smartphones, built-in accelerometers can be used as a pedometer and built-in magnetometer as a compass heading provider.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] **Pedestrian dead reckoning** (**PDR**) can be used to supplement other navigation methods in a similar way to automotive navigation, or to extend navigation into areas where other navigation systems are unavailable.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] In a simple implementation, the user holds their phone in front of them, and each step causes their position to move forward a fixed distance in the direction measured by the compass.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] Accuracy is limited by the sensor precision, magnetic disturbances inside structures, and unknown variables such as carrying position and stride length.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] Another challenge is differentiating walking from running, and recognizing movements like bicycling, climbing stairs, or riding an elevator.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] Before phone-based systems existed, many custom PDR systems existed.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] While a pedometer can only be used to measure linear distance traveled, PDR systems have an embedded magnetometer for heading measurement.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] Custom PDR systems can take many forms including special boots, belts, and watches, where the variability of carrying position has been minimized to better utilize magnetometer heading.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] True dead reckoning is fairly complicated, as it is not only important to minimize basic drift, but also to handle different carrying scenarios and movements, as well as hardware differences across phone models.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] The south-pointing chariot was an ancient Chinese device consisting of a two-wheeled horse-drawn vehicle which carried a pointer that was intended always to aim to the south, no matter how the chariot turned.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] The chariot pre-dated the navigational use of the magnetic compass, and could not *detect* the direction that was south.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] Instead it used a kind of **directional dead reckoning**: at the start of a journey, the pointer was aimed southward by hand, using local knowledge or astronomical observations e.g. of the Pole Star.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] Errors, as always with dead reckoning, would accumulate as distance traveled increased.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] Networked games and simulation tools routinely use dead reckoning to predict where an actor should be right now, using its last known kinematic state (position, velocity, acceleration, orientation, and angular velocity).
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] This is primarily needed because it is impractical to send network updates at the rate that most games run, 60 Hz.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] This formula is used to move the object until a new update is received over the network.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] At that point, the problem is that there are now two kinematic states: the currently estimated position and the just received, actual position.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] Resolving these two states in a believable way can be quite complex.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] One approach is to create a curve (e.g. cubic Bézier splines, centripetal Catmull–Rom splines, and Hermite curves) between the two states while still projecting into the future.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] Another technique is to use projective velocity blending, which is the blending of two projections (last known and current) where the current projection uses a blending between the last known and current velocity over a set time.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] The first equation calculates a blended velocity $V_{b}$ given the client-side velocity at the time of the last server update $V_{0}$ and the last known server-side velocity ${\acute {V}}_{0}$ .
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] This essentially blends from the client-side velocity towards the server-side velocity for a smooth transition.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] Note that ${\hat {T}}$ should go from zero (at the time of the server update) to one (at the time at which the next update should be arriving).
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] A late server update is unproblematic as long as ${\hat {T}}$ remains at one.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] Next, two positions are calculated: firstly, the blended velocity $V_{b}$ and the last known server-side acceleration ${\acute {A}}_{0}$ are used to calculate $P_{t}$ .
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] This is a position which is projected from the client-side start position $P_{0}$ based on $T_{t}$ , the time which has passed since the last server update.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] Secondly, the same equation is used with the last known server-side parameters to calculate the position projected from the last known server-side position ${\acute {P}}_{0}$ and velocity ${\acute {V}}_{0}$ , resulting in ${\acute {P}}_{t}$ .
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] Finally, the new position to display on the client $Pos$ is the result of interpolating from the projected position based on client information $P_{t}$ towards the projected position based on the last known server information ${\acute {P}}_{t}$ .
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] The resulting movement smoothly resolves the discrepancy between client-side and server-side information, even if this server-side information arrives infrequently or inconsistently.
[src:client-side-prediction/dead-reckoning] It is also free of oscillations which spline-based interpolation may suffer from.
[src:client-side-prediction/extrapolation] In mathematics, **extrapolation** is a type of estimation, beyond the original observation range, of the value of a variable on the basis of its relationship with another variable.
[src:client-side-prediction/extrapolation] It is similar to interpolation, which produces estimates between known observations, but extrapolation is subject to greater uncertainty and a higher risk of producing meaningless results.
[src:client-side-prediction/extrapolation] Extrapolation may also mean extension of a method, assuming similar methods will be applicable.
[src:client-side-prediction/extrapolation] Extrapolation may also apply to human experience to project, extend, or expand known experience into an area not known or previously experienced.
[src:client-side-prediction/extrapolation] By doing so, one makes an assumption of the unknown (for example, a driver may extrapolate road conditions beyond what is currently visible and these extrapolations may be correct or incorrect).
[src:client-side-prediction/extrapolation] The extrapolation method can be applied in the interior reconstruction problem.
[src:client-side-prediction/extrapolation] A sound choice of which extrapolation method to apply relies on *a priori knowledge* of the process that created the existing data points.
[src:client-side-prediction/extrapolation] Some experts have proposed the use of causal forces in the evaluation of extrapolation methods.
[src:client-side-prediction/extrapolation] Crucial questions are, for example, if the data can be assumed to be continuous, smooth, possibly periodic, etc.
[src:client-side-prediction/extrapolation] Linear extrapolation means creating a tangent line at the end of the known data and extending it beyond that limit.
[src:client-side-prediction/extrapolation] Linear extrapolation will only provide good results when used to extend the graph of an approximately linear function or not too far beyond the known data.
[src:client-side-prediction/extrapolation] (which is identical to linear interpolation if $x_{k-1}<x_{*}<x_{k}$ ).
[src:client-side-prediction/extrapolation] It is possible to include more than two points, and averaging the slope of the linear interpolant, by regression-like techniques, on the data points chosen to be included.
[src:client-side-prediction/extrapolation] A polynomial curve can be created through the entire known data or just near the end (two points for linear extrapolation, three points for quadratic extrapolation, etc.).
[src:client-side-prediction/extrapolation] The resulting curve can then be extended beyond the end of the known data.
[src:client-side-prediction/extrapolation] Polynomial extrapolation is typically done by means of Lagrange interpolation or using Newton's method of finite differences to create a Newton series that fits the data.
[src:client-side-prediction/extrapolation] The resulting polynomial may be used to extrapolate the data.
[src:client-side-prediction/extrapolation] High-order polynomial extrapolation must be used with due care.
[src:client-side-prediction/extrapolation] For the example data set and problem in the figure above, anything above order 1 (linear extrapolation) will possibly yield unusable values; an error estimate of the extrapolated value will grow with the degree of the polynomial extrapolation.
[src:client-side-prediction/extrapolation] A conic section can be created using five points near the end of the known data.
[src:client-side-prediction/extrapolation] If the conic section created is an ellipse or circle, when extrapolated it will loop back and rejoin itself.
[src:client-side-prediction/extrapolation] An extrapolated parabola or hyperbola will not rejoin itself, but may curve back relative to the X-axis.
[src:client-side-prediction/extrapolation] This type of extrapolation could be done with a conic sections template (on paper) or with a computer.
[src:client-side-prediction/extrapolation] French curve extrapolation is a method suitable for any distribution that has a tendency to be exponential, but with accelerating or decelerating factors.
[src:client-side-prediction/extrapolation] This method has been used successfully in providing forecast projections of the growth of HIV/AIDS in the UK since 1987 and variant CJD in the UK for a number of years.
[src:client-side-prediction/extrapolation] Another study has shown that extrapolation can produce the same quality of forecasting results as more complex forecasting strategies.
[src:client-side-prediction/extrapolation] Can be created with 3 points of a sequence and the "moment" or "index", this type of extrapolation have 100% accuracy in predictions in a big percentage of known series database (OEIS).
[src:client-side-prediction/extrapolation] Typically, the quality of a particular method of extrapolation is limited by the assumptions about the function made by the method.
[src:client-side-prediction/extrapolation] If the method assumes the data are smooth, then a non-smooth function will be poorly extrapolated.
[src:client-side-prediction/extrapolation] In terms of complex time series, some experts have discovered that extrapolation is more accurate when performed through the decomposition of causal forces.
[src:client-side-prediction/extrapolation] Even for proper assumptions about the function, the extrapolation can diverge severely from the function.
[src:client-side-prediction/extrapolation] The classic example is truncated power series representations of sin(*x*) and related trigonometric functions.
[src:client-side-prediction/extrapolation] For instance, taking only data from near the *x* = 0, we may estimate that the function behaves as sin(*x*) ~ *x*.
[src:client-side-prediction/extrapolation] In the neighborhood of *x* = 0, this is an excellent estimate.
[src:client-side-prediction/extrapolation] Away from *x* = 0 however, the extrapolation moves arbitrarily away from the *x*-axis while sin(*x*) remains in the interval [−1, 1].
[src:client-side-prediction/extrapolation] I.e., the error increases without bound.
[src:client-side-prediction/extrapolation] Taking more terms in the power series of sin(*x*) around *x* = 0 will produce better agreement over a larger interval near *x* = 0, but will produce extrapolations that eventually diverge away from the *x*-axis even faster than the linear approximation.
[src:client-side-prediction/extrapolation] This divergence is a specific property of extrapolation methods and is only circumvented when the functional forms assumed by the extrapolation method (inadvertently or intentionally due to additional information) accurately represent the nature of the function being extrapolated.
[src:client-side-prediction/extrapolation] For particular problems, this additional information may be available, but in the general case, it is impossible to satisfy all possible function behaviors with a workably small set of potential behavior.
[src:client-side-prediction/extrapolation] In complex analysis, a problem of extrapolation may be converted into an interpolation problem by the change of variable ${\hat {z}}=1/z$ .
[src:client-side-prediction/extrapolation] This transform exchanges the part of the complex plane inside the unit circle with the part of the complex plane outside of the unit circle.
[src:client-side-prediction/extrapolation] In particular, the compactification point at infinity is mapped to the origin and vice versa.
[src:client-side-prediction/extrapolation] Care must be taken with this transform however, since the original function may have had "features", for example poles and other singularities, at infinity that were not evident from the sampled data.
[src:client-side-prediction/extrapolation] Another problem of extrapolation is loosely related to the problem of analytic continuation, where (typically) a power series representation of a function is expanded at one of its points of convergence to produce a power series with a larger radius of convergence.
[src:client-side-prediction/extrapolation] In effect, a set of data from a small region is used to extrapolate a function onto a larger region.
[src:client-side-prediction/extrapolation] Again, analytic continuation can be thwarted by function features that were not evident from the initial data.
[src:client-side-prediction/extrapolation] Also, one may use sequence transformations like Padé approximants and Levin-type sequence transformations as extrapolation methods that lead to a summation of power series that are divergent outside the original radius of convergence.
[src:client-side-prediction/extrapolation] In this case, one often obtains rational approximants.
[src:client-side-prediction/extrapolation] Extrapolation arguments are informal and unquantified arguments which assert that something is probably true beyond the range of values for which it is known to be true.
[src:client-side-prediction/extrapolation] Such arguments are widely used in biology in extrapolating from animal studies to humans and from pilot studies to a broader population.
[src:client-side-prediction/extrapolation] Like slippery slope arguments, extrapolation arguments may be strong or weak depending on such factors as how far the extrapolation goes beyond the known range.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] In the mathematical field of numerical analysis, **interpolation** is a type of estimation, a method of constructing (finding) new data points based on the range of a discrete set of known data points.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] In engineering and science, one often has a number of data points, obtained by sampling or experimentation, which represent the values of a function for a limited number of values of the independent variable.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] It is often required to **interpolate**; that is, estimate the value of that function for an intermediate value of the independent variable.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] A closely related problem is the approximation of a complicated function by a simple function.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] Suppose the formula for some given function is known, but too complicated to evaluate efficiently.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] A few data points from the original function can be interpolated to produce a simpler function which is still fairly close to the original.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] The resulting gain in simplicity may outweigh the loss from interpolation error and give better performance in calculation process.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] As an example we will use points from the equation $f(x)=sin(x)$ to demonstrate various interpolation methods.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] We describe some methods of interpolation, differing in such properties as: accuracy, cost, number of data points needed, and smoothness of the resulting interpolant function.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] The simplest interpolation method is to locate the nearest data value, and assign the same value.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] In simple problems, this method is unlikely to be used, as linear interpolation (see below) is almost as easy, but in higher-dimensional multivariate interpolation, this could be a favourable choice for its speed and simplicity.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] One of the simplest methods is linear interpolation (sometimes known as lerp).
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] Consider the above example of estimating *f*(2.5).
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] Linear interpolation is quick and easy, but it is not very precise.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] Another disadvantage is that the interpolant is not differentiable at the point *x**k*.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] The following error estimate shows that linear interpolation is not very precise.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] Denote the function which we want to interpolate by *g*, and suppose that *x* lies between *x**a* and *x**b* and that *g* is twice continuously differentiable.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] In words, the error is proportional to the square of the distance between the data points.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] The error in some other methods, including polynomial interpolation and spline interpolation (described below), is proportional to higher powers of the distance between the data points.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] These methods also produce smoother interpolants.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] Polynomial interpolation is a generalization of linear interpolation.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] Note that the linear interpolant is a linear function.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] We now replace this interpolant with a polynomial of higher degree.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] Generally, if we have *n* data points, there is exactly one polynomial of degree at most *n*−1 going through all the data points.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] The interpolation error is proportional to the distance between the data points to the power *n*.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] Furthermore, the interpolant is a polynomial and thus infinitely differentiable.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] So, we see that polynomial interpolation overcomes most of the problems of linear interpolation.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] However, polynomial interpolation also has some disadvantages.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] Calculating the interpolating polynomial is computationally expensive (see computational complexity) compared to linear interpolation.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] Furthermore, polynomial interpolation may exhibit oscillatory artifacts, especially at the end points (see Runge's phenomenon).
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] Polynomial interpolation can estimate local maxima and minima that are outside the range of the samples, unlike linear interpolation.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] However, these maxima and minima may exceed the theoretical range of the function; for example, a function that is always positive may have an interpolant with negative values, and whose inverse therefore contains false vertical asymptotes.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] More generally, the shape of the resulting curve, especially for very high or low values of the independent variable, may be contrary to commonsense; that is, to what is known about the experimental system which has generated the data points.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] These disadvantages can be reduced by using spline interpolation or restricting attention to Chebyshev polynomials.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] Linear interpolation uses a linear function for each of intervals [*x**k*,*x**k+1*].
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] Spline interpolation uses low-degree polynomials in each of the intervals, and chooses the polynomial pieces such that they fit smoothly together.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] The resulting function is called a spline.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] For instance, the natural cubic spline is piecewise cubic and twice continuously differentiable.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] Furthermore, its second derivative is zero at the end points.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] Like polynomial interpolation, spline interpolation incurs a smaller error than linear interpolation, while the interpolant is smoother and easier to evaluate than the high-degree polynomials used in polynomial interpolation.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] However, the global nature of the basis functions leads to ill-conditioning.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] This is completely mitigated by using splines of compact support, such as are implemented in Boost.Math and discussed in Kress.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] Depending on the underlying discretisation of fields, different interpolants may be required.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] In contrast to other interpolation methods, which estimate functions on target points, mimetic interpolation evaluates the integral of fields on target lines, areas or volumes, depending on the type of field (scalar, vector, pseudo-vector or pseudo-scalar).
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] A key feature of mimetic interpolation is that vector calculus identities are satisfied, including Stokes' theorem and the divergence theorem.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] As a result, mimetic interpolation conserves line, area and volume integrals.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] Conservation of line integrals might be desirable when interpolating the electric field, for instance, since the line integral gives the electric potential difference at the endpoints of the integration path.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] Mimetic interpolation ensures that the error of estimating the line integral of an electric field is the same as the error obtained by interpolating the potential at the end points of the integration path, regardless of the length of the integration path.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] Linear, bilinear and trilinear interpolation are also considered mimetic, even if it is the field values that are conserved (not the integral of the field).
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] Apart from linear interpolation, area weighted interpolation can be considered one of the first mimetic interpolation methods to have been developed.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] The Theory of Functional Connections (TFC) is a mathematical framework specifically developed for functional interpolation.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] Given any interpolant that satisfies a set of constraints, TFC derives a functional that represents the entire family of interpolants satisfying those constraints, including those that are discontinuous or partially defined.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] These functionals identify the subspace of functions where the solution to a constrained optimization problem resides.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] Consequently, TFC transforms constrained optimization problems into equivalent unconstrained formulations.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] This transformation has proven highly effective in the solution of differential equations.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] TFC achieves this by constructing a constrained functional (a function of a free function), that inherently satisfies given constraints regardless of the expression of the free function.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] This simplifies solving various types of equations and significantly improves the efficiency and accuracy of methods like Physics-Informed Neural Networks (PINNs).
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] TFC offers advantages over traditional methods like Lagrange multipliers and spectral methods by directly addressing constraints analytically and avoiding iterative procedures, although it cannot currently handle inequality constraints.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] Interpolation is a common way to approximate functions.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] Given a function $f:[a,b]\to \mathbb {R}$ with a set of points $x_{1},x_{2},\dots ,x_{n}\in [a,b]$ one can form a function $s:[a,b]\to \mathbb {R}$ such that $f(x_{i})=s(x_{i})$ for $i=1,2,\dots ,n$ (that is, that s interpolates f at these points).
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] In general, an interpolant need not be a good approximation, but there are well known and often reasonable conditions where it will.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] For example, if $f\in C^{4}([a,b])$ (four times continuously differentiable) then cubic spline interpolation has an error bound given by $\|f-s\|_{\infty }\leq C\|f^{(4)}\|_{\infty }h^{4}$ where $h\max _{i=1,2,\dots ,n-1}|x_{i+1}-x_{i}|$ and C is a constant.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] Gaussian process is a powerful non-linear interpolation tool.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] Many popular interpolation tools are actually equivalent to particular Gaussian processes.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] Gaussian processes can be used not only for fitting an interpolant that passes exactly through the given data points but also for regression; that is, for fitting a curve through noisy data.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] In the geostatistics community Gaussian process regression is also known as Kriging.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] Inverse Distance Weighting (IDW) is a spatial interpolation method that estimates values based on nearby data points, with closer points having more influence.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] It uses an inverse power law for weighting, where higher power values emphasize local effects, while lower values create a smoother surface.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] IDW is widely used in GIS, meteorology, and environmental modeling for its simplicity but may produce artifacts in clustered or uneven data.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] Other forms of interpolation can be constructed by picking a different class of interpolants.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] For instance, rational interpolation is **interpolation** by rational functions using Padé approximant, and trigonometric interpolation is interpolation by trigonometric polynomials using Fourier series.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] The Whittaker–Shannon interpolation formula can be used if the number of data points is infinite or if the function to be interpolated has compact support.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] Sometimes, we know not only the value of the function that we want to interpolate, at some points, but also its derivative.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] This leads to Hermite interpolation problems.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] When each data point is itself a function, it can be useful to see the interpolation problem as a partial advection problem between each data point.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] This idea leads to the displacement interpolation problem used in transportation theory.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] Multivariate interpolation is the interpolation of functions of more than one variable.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] Methods include nearest-neighbor interpolation, bilinear interpolation and bicubic interpolation in two dimensions, and trilinear interpolation in three dimensions.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] They can be applied to gridded or scattered data.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] Mimetic interpolation generalizes to n dimensional spaces where $n>3$ .
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] In this application there is a specific requirement that the harmonic content of the original signal be preserved without creating aliased harmonic content of the original signal above the original Nyquist limit of the signal (that is, above fs/2 of the original signal sample rate).
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] An early and fairly elementary discussion on this subject can be found in Rabiner and Crochiere's book *Multirate Digital Signal Processing*.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] The term *extrapolation* is used to find data points outside the range of known data points.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] In curve fitting problems, the constraint that the interpolant has to go exactly through the data points is relaxed.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] It is only required to approach the data points as closely as possible (within some other constraints).
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] This requires parameterizing the potential interpolants and having some way of measuring the error.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] In the simplest case this leads to least squares approximation.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] Approximation theory studies how to find the best approximation to a given function by another function from some predetermined class, and how good this approximation is.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] This clearly yields a bound on how well the interpolant can approximate the unknown function.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] If we consider x as a variable in a topological space, and the function $f(x)$ mapping to a Banach space, then the problem is treated as "interpolation of operators".
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] The classical results about interpolation of operators are the Riesz–Thorin theorem and the Marcinkiewicz theorem.
[src:client-side-prediction/interpolation] There are also many other subsequent results.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] Latency is physically a consequence of the limited velocity at which any physical interaction can propagate.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] The magnitude of this velocity is always less than or equal to the speed of light.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] Therefore, every physical system with any physical separation (distance) between cause and effect will experience some sort of latency, regardless of the nature of the stimulation to which it has been exposed.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] The precise definition of latency depends on the system being observed or the nature of the simulation.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] In communications, the lower limit of latency is determined by the medium being used to transfer information.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] In reliable two-way communication systems, latency limits the maximum rate at which information can be transmitted, as there is often a limit on the amount of information that is in-flight at any given moment.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] Perceptible latency has a strong effect on user satisfaction and usability in the field of human–machine interaction.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] Online games are sensitive to latency (lag), since fast response times to new events occurring during a game session are rewarded while slow response times may carry penalties.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] Due to a delay in transmission of game events, a player with a high-latency internet connection may show slow responses in spite of appropriate reaction time.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] This gives players with low-latency connections a technical advantage.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] Trading using computers has developed to the point where millisecond improvements in network speeds offer a competitive advantage for financial institutions.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] However, in a non-trivial network, a typical packet will be forwarded over multiple links and gateways, each of which will not begin to forward the packet until it has been completely received.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] In such a network, the minimal latency is the sum of the transmission delay of each link, plus the forwarding latency of each gateway.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] In practice, minimal latency also includes queuing and processing delays.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] Queuing delay occurs when a gateway receives multiple packets from different sources heading toward the same destination.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] Since typically only one packet can be transmitted at a time, some of the packets must queue for transmission, incurring additional delay.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] Processing delays are incurred while a gateway determines what to do with a newly received packet.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] Bufferbloat can also cause increased latency that is an order of magnitude or more.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] The combination of propagation, serialization, queuing, and processing delays often produces a complex and variable network latency profile.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] Latency limits total throughput in reliable two-way communication systems as described by the bandwidth-delay product.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] Latency in optical fiber is largely a function of the speed of light.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] This would equate to a latency of 3.33 μs for every kilometer of path length.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] The index of refraction of most fiber optic cables is about 1.5, meaning that light travels about 1.5 times as fast in a vacuum as it does in the cable.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] This works out to about 5.0 μs of latency for every kilometer.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] In shorter metro networks, higher latency can be experienced due to extra distance in building risers and cross-connects.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] To calculate the latency of a connection, one has to know the distance traveled by the fiber, which is rarely a straight line, since it has to traverse geographic contours and obstacles, such as roads and railway tracks, as well as other rights-of-way.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] Due to imperfections in the fiber, light degrades as it is transmitted through it.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] For distances of greater than 100 kilometers, amplifiers or regenerators are deployed.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] Latency introduced by these components needs to be taken into account.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] Low Earth orbit is sometimes used to cut this delay, at the expense of more complicated satellite tracking on the ground and requiring more satellites in the satellite constellation to ensure continuous coverage.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] Audio latency is the delay between when an audio signal enters and when it emerges from a system.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] Potential contributors to latency in an audio system include analog-to-digital conversion, buffering, digital signal processing, transmission time, digital-to-analog conversion and the speed of sound in air.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] Video latency refers to the degree of delay between the time a transfer of a video stream is requested and the actual time that transfer begins.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] Networks that exhibit relatively small delays are known as low-latency networks, while their counterparts are known as high-latency networks.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] Any individual workflow within a system of workflows can be subject to some type of operational latency.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] It may even be the case that an individual system may have more than one type of latency, depending on the type of participant or goal-seeking behavior.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] This is best illustrated by the following two examples involving air travel.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] From the point of view of a passenger, latency can be described as follows.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] Suppose John Doe flies from London to New York.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] The latency of his trip is the time it takes him to go from his house in England to the hotel he is staying at in New York.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] This is independent of the throughput of the London-New York air link, whether there were 100 passengers a day making the trip or 10000, the latency of the trip would remain the same.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] From the point of view of flight operations personnel, latency can be entirely different.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] Consider the staff at the London and New York airports.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] Only a limited number of planes are able to make the transatlantic journey, so when one lands, they must prepare it for the return trip as quickly as possible.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] However, cleaning, refueling and loading the cargo can be done at the same time.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] Passengers can only be loaded after cleaning is complete.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] The people involved in the turnaround are interested only in the time it takes for their individual tasks.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] When all of the tasks are done at the same time, however, it is possible to reduce the latency to the length of the longest task.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] If some steps have prerequisites, it becomes more difficult to perform all steps in parallel.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] In the example above, the requirement to clean the plane before loading passengers results in a minimum latency longer than any single task.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] Any mechanical process encounters limitations modeled by Newtonian physics.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] The behavior of disk drives provides an example of mechanical latency.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] Here, it is the time seek time for the actuator arm to be positioned above the appropriate track and then rotational latency for the data encoded on a platter to rotate from its current position to a position under the disk read-and-write head.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] Computers run instructions in the context of a process.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] In the context of computer multitasking, the execution of the process can be postponed if other processes are also executing.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] In addition, the operating system can schedule when to perform the action that the process is commanding.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] For example, suppose a process commands that a computer card's voltage output be set high-low-high-low and so on at a rate of 1000 Hz.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] The operating system schedules the process for each transition (high-low or low-high) based on a hardware clock, such as the High Precision Event Timer.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] The latency is the delay between the events generated by the hardware clock and the actual transitions of voltage from high to low or low to high.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] Many desktop operating systems have performance limitations that create additional latency.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] The problem may be mitigated with real-time extensions and patches such as PREEMPT RT.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] On embedded systems, the real-time execution of instructions is often supported by a real-time operating system.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] Note that in software systems, benchmarking against *average* and *median* latency can be misleading because a few outliers can distort them.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] Instead, software architects and software developers should use "99th percentile".
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] In simulation applications, latency refers to the time delay, often measured in milliseconds, between initial input and output clearly discernible to the simulator trainee or simulator subject.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] Latency is sometimes also called *transport delay*.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] Some authorities distinguish between latency and transport delay by using the term *latency* in the sense of the extra time delay of a system over and above the reaction time of the vehicle being simulated, but this requires detailed knowledge of the vehicle dynamics and can be controversial.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] In simulators with both visual and motion systems, it is particularly important that the latency of the motion system not be greater than of the visual system, or symptoms of simulator sickness may result.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] This is because, in the real world, motion cues are those of acceleration and are quickly transmitted to the brain, typically in less than 50 milliseconds; this is followed some milliseconds later by a perception of change in the visual scene.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] The visual scene change is essentially one of change of perspective or displacement of objects, such as the horizon, which takes some time to build up to discernible amounts after the initial acceleration that caused the displacement.
[src:client-side-prediction/latency-engineering] A simulator should, therefore, reflect the real-world situation by ensuring that the motion latency is equal to or less than that of the visual system and not the other way round.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] Due to multiplayer games allowing players to interact with other individuals, they provide an element of social communication absent from single-player games.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] The history of multiplayer video games extends over several decades, tracing back to the emergence of electronic gaming in the mid-20th century.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] One of the earliest instances of multiplayer interaction was witnessed with the development of *Spacewar!* in 1962 for the DEC PDP-1 computer by Steve Russell and colleagues at the MIT.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] During the late 1970s and early 1980s, multiplayer gaming gained momentum within the arcade scene with classics like *Pong* and *Tank*.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] The transition to home gaming consoles in the 1980s further popularized multiplayer gaming.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] Titles like *Super Mario Bros.* for the NES and *Golden Axe* for the Sega Genesis introduced cooperative and competitive gameplay.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] Additionally, LAN gaming emerged in the late 1980s, enabling players to connect multiple computers for multiplayer gameplay, popularized by titles like *Doom* and *Warcraft: Orcs & Humans*.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] Players can also play together in the same room using splitscreen.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] Some of the earliest video games were two-player games, including early sports games (such as 1958's *Tennis For Two* and 1972's *Pong*), early shooter games such as *Spacewar!* (1962) and early racing video games such as *Astro Race* (1973).
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] The first examples of multiplayer real-time games were developed on the PLATO system about 1973.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] Multi-user games developed on this system included 1973's Empire and 1974's Spasim; the latter was an early first-person shooter.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] Other early video games included turn-based multiplayer modes, popular in tabletop arcade machines.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] In such games, play is alternated at some point (often after the loss of a life).
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] All players' scores are often displayed onscreen so players can see their relative standing.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] Danielle Bunten Berry created some of the first multiplayer video games, such as her debut, *Wheeler Dealers* (1978) and her most notable work, *M.U.L.E.* (1983).
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] Kemeny wrote in 1972 that software running on the Dartmouth Time-Sharing System (DTSS) had recently gained the ability to support multiple simultaneous users, and that games were the first use of the functionality.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] DTSS's popular American football game, he said, now supported head-to-head play by two humans.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] The university's computer system had hundreds of terminals, connected (via serial lines) through cluster PDP-11s for student, teacher, and staff access.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] The games had a program running on each terminal (for each player), sharing a segment of shared memory (known as the "high segment" in the OS TOPS-10).
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] The games became popular, and the university often banned them because of their RAM use.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] STAR was based on 1974's single-user, turn-oriented BASIC program STAR, written by Michael O'Shaughnessy at UNH.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] Wasserman and Stryker in 1980 described in *BYTE* how to network two Commodore PET computers with a cable.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] Their article includes a type-in, two-player Hangman, and describes the authors' more-sophisticated *Flash Attack*.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] SuperSet Software's *Snipes* (1981) uses networking technology that would become Novell NetWare.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] Digital Equipment Corporation distributed another multi-user version of *Star Trek*, Decwar, without real-time screen updating; it was widely distributed to universities with DECsystem-10s.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] In 1981 Cliff Zimmerman wrote an homage to *Star Trek* in MACRO-10 for DECsystem-10s and -20s using VT100-series graphics.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] "VTtrek" pitted four Federation players against four Klingons in a three-dimensional universe.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] Networked multiplayer gaming modes are known as "netplay".
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] The first popular video-game title with a Local Area Network(LAN) version, 1991's Spectre for the Apple Macintosh, featured AppleTalk support for up to eight players.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] Spectre's popularity was partially attributed to the display of a player's name above their cybertank.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] There followed 1993's Doom, whose first network version allowed four simultaneous players.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] Play-by-email multiplayer games use email to communicate between computers.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] Other turn-based variations not requiring players to be online simultaneously are Play-by-post gaming and Play-by-Internet.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] Some online games are "massively multiplayer", with many players participating simultaneously.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] Two massively multiplayer genres are MMORPG (such as *World of Warcraft* or *EverQuest*) and MMORTS.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] First-person shooters have become popular multiplayer games; *Battlefield 1942* and *Counter-Strike* have little (or no) single-player gameplay.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] Developer and gaming site OMGPOP's library included multiplayer Flash games for the casual player until it was shut down in 2013.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] Some networked multiplayer games, including MUDs and massively multiplayer online games (MMOs) such as RuneScape, omit a single-player mode.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] The largest MMO in 2008 was *World of Warcraft*, with over 10 million registered players worldwide.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] *World of Warcraft* would hit its peak at 12 million players two years later in 2010, and in 2023 earned the Guinness World Record for best selling MMO video game.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] This category of games requires multiple machines to connect via the Internet; before the Internet became popular, MUDs were played on time-sharing computer systems and games like *Doom* were played on a LAN.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] Beginning with the Sega NetLink in 1996, Game.com in 1997 and Dreamcast in 2000, game consoles support network gaming over LANs and the Internet.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] Many mobile phones and handheld consoles also offer wireless gaming with Bluetooth (or similar) technology.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] By the early 2010s online gaming had become a mainstay of console platforms such as Xbox and PlayStation.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] During the 2010s, as the number of Internet users increased, two new video game genres rapidly gained worldwide popularity – multiplayer online battle arena and battle royale game, both designed exclusively for multiplayer gameplay over the Internet.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] Over time the number of people playing video games has increased.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] In 2020, the majority of households in the United States have an occupant that plays video games, and 65% of gamers play multiplayer games with others either online or in person.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] For some games, "multiplayer" implies that players are playing on the same gaming system or network.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] This applies to all arcade games, but also to a number of console, and personal computer games too.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] Turn-based games such as chess also lend themselves to single system single screen and even to a single controller.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] Multiple types of games allow players to use local multiplayer.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] The term "local co-op" or "couch co-op" refers to local multiplayer games played in a cooperative manner on the same system; these may use split-screen or some other display method.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] Hot-seat games are typically turn-based games with only one controller or input set – such as a single keyboard/mouse on the system.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] Players rotate using the input device to perform their turn such that each is taking a turn on the "hot-seat".
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] Not all local multiplayer games are played on the same console or personal computer.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] Some local multiplayer games are played over a LAN.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] This involves multiple devices using one local network to play together.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] Networked multiplayer games on LAN eliminate common problems faced when playing online such as lag and anonymity.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] Games played on a LAN network are the focus of LAN parties.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] While local co-op and LAN parties still take place, there has been a decrease in both due to an increasing number of players and games utilizing online multiplayer gaming.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] Online multiplayer games connect players over a wide area network (a common example being the Internet).
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] Unlike local multiplayer, players playing online multiplayer are not restricted to the same local network.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] This allows players to interact with others from a much greater distance.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] Playing multiplayer online offers the benefits of distance, but it also comes with its own unique challenges.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] Gamers refer to latency using the term "ping", after a utility which measures round-trip network communication delays (by the use of ICMP packets).
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] A player on a DSL connection with a 50-ms ping can react faster than a modem user with a 350-ms average latency.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] Other problems include packet loss and choke, which can prevent a player from "registering" their actions with a server.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] In first-person shooters, this problem appears when bullets hit the enemy without damage.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] The player's connection is not the only factor; some servers are slower than others.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] A server that is geographically closer to the player's connection will often provide a lower ping.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] Data packets travel faster to a location that is closer to them.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] How far the device is from an internet connection (router) can also affect latency.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] Asymmetrical multiplayer is a type of gameplay in which players can have significantly different roles or abilities from each other – enough to provide a significantly different experience of the game.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] A first-person shooter that adopts the asymmetrical multiplayer system is Tom Clancy's Rainbow Six Siege.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] Giving players their own special operator changes every player's experience.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] This puts an emphasis on players improvising their own game plan given the abilities their character has.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] In games with stronger elements of asymmetry, one player/team may have one gameplay experience (or be in softly asymmetric roles) while the other player or team play in a drastically different way, with different mechanics, a different type of objective, or both.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] Examples of games with strong asymmetry include *Dead by Daylight*, *Evolve*, and *Left 4 Dead*.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] Deathloop featured opt‑in asymmetric PvP and Elden Ring’s evolved Souls invasions at scale.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] Depending on the game, objectives and story, the invading player(s) goals, roles, and own objectives will be different.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] Asynchronous multiplayer is a form of multiplayer gameplay where players are not necessarily playing at the same time.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] This form of multiplayer game has its origins in play-by-mail games, where players would send their moves through postal mail to a game master, who then would compile and send out results for the next turn.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] Play-by-mail games transitioned to electronic form as play-by-email games.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] Similar games were developed for bulletin board systems, such as *Trade Wars*, where the turn structure may not be as rigorous and allow players to take actions at any time in a persistence space alongside all other players, a concept known as sporadic play.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] These types of asynchronous multiplayer games waned with the widespread availability of the Internet which allowed players to play against each other simultaneously, but remains an option in many strategy-related games, such as the *Civilization* series.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] Coordination of turns are subsequently managed by one computer or a centralized server.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] Further, many mobile games are based on sporadic play and use social interactions with other players, lacking direct player versus player game modes but allowing players to influence other players' games, coordinated through central game servers, another facet of asynchronous play.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] Online cheating (in gaming) usually refers to modifying the game experience to give one player an advantage over others, such as using an "aimbot" – a program which automatically locks the player's crosshairs onto a target – in shooting games.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] This is also known as "hacking" or "glitching" ("glitching" refers to using a glitch, or a mistake in the code of a game, whereas "hacking" is manipulating the code of a game).
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] Cheating in video games is often done via a third-party program that modifies the game's code at runtime to give one or more players an advantage.
[src:client-side-prediction/multiplayer-video-game] In other situations, it is frequently done by changing the game's files to change the game's mechanics.
[src:client-side-prediction/netcode] Players often blame "bad netcode" when they experience lag or reverse state transitions when synchronization between players is lost.
[src:client-side-prediction/netcode] Although these events are sometimes caused by bugs, other networking-related causes include high latency between server and client, packet loss, or network congestion.
[src:client-side-prediction/netcode] Depending on the game implementation, these issues can also be caused by non-network factors such as frame rendering time or inconsistent frame rate.
[src:client-side-prediction/netcode] Netcode is often designed to mask networking irregularities and create a synchronous and smooth gamestate across multiple users.
[src:client-side-prediction/netcode] There are two main resolutions to this conflict implemented in modern games: delay-based and rollback-based resolution.
[src:client-side-prediction/netcode] The classic solution to this problem is the use of a delay-based netcode.
[src:client-side-prediction/netcode] When the inputs of a remote player arrive late, the game delays the inputs of the local player accordingly to synchronize the two inputs and run them simultaneously.
[src:client-side-prediction/netcode] This added delay can be disruptive for players (especially when latency is high), but overall the change is not very noticeable.
[src:client-side-prediction/netcode] However, these delays can be inconsistent due to sudden fluctuations in current latency.
[src:client-side-prediction/netcode] Should the latency between players exceed an established buffer window for the remote player, the game must wait, causing the screens to "freeze".
[src:client-side-prediction/netcode] This occurs because a delay-based netcode does not allow the simulation to continue until it receives the inputs from all the players in the frame in question.
[src:client-side-prediction/netcode] This variable delay causes an inconsistent and unresponsive experience compared to offline play (or to a LAN game), and can negatively affect player performance in timing-sensitive and fast-paced genres such as fighting games.
[src:client-side-prediction/netcode] An alternative system to the previous netcode is rollback netcode.
[src:client-side-prediction/netcode] Some games utilize a hybrid solution in order to disguise these "jumps" (which can become problematic as latency between players grows, as there is less and less time to react to other players' actions) with a fixed input delay and then rollback being used.
[src:client-side-prediction/netcode] Rollback is quite effective at concealing lag spikes or other issues related to inconsistencies in the users' connections, as predictions are often correct and players do not even notice.
[src:client-side-prediction/netcode] Nevertheless, this system can be troublesome whenever a client's game slows down (usually due to overheating), since rift problems can be caused leading to an exchange of tickets between machines at unequal rates.
[src:client-side-prediction/netcode] This generates visual glitches that interrupt the gameplay of those players that receive inputs at a slower pace, while the player whose game is slowed down will have an advantage over the rest by receiving inputs from others at a normal rate (this is known as one-sided rollback).
[src:client-side-prediction/netcode] There is a popular MIT-licensed library named GGPO designed to help implement rollback networking to games (mainly fighting games).
[src:client-side-prediction/netcode] Latency is unavoidable in online games, and the quality of the player's experience is strictly tied to this (the more latency there is between players, the greater the feeling that the game is not responsive to their inputs).
[src:client-side-prediction/netcode] The latency of the players' network (which is largely out of a game's control) is not the only factor in question, but also the latency inherent in the way the game simulations are run.
[src:client-side-prediction/netcode] There are several lag compensation methods used to disguise or cope with latency (especially with high latency values).
[src:client-side-prediction/netcode] A single update of a game simulation is known as a tick.
[src:client-side-prediction/netcode] The rate at which the simulation is run on a server is often referred to as the server's tickrate; this is essentially the server equivalent of a client's frame rate, absent any rendering system.
[src:client-side-prediction/netcode] Tickrate is limited by the length of time it takes to run the simulation, and is often intentionally limited further to reduce instability introduced by a fluctuating tickrate, and to reduce CPU and data transmission costs.
[src:client-side-prediction/netcode] A lower tickrate increases latency in the synchronization of the game simulation between the server and clients.
[src:client-side-prediction/netcode] A lower tickrate also naturally reduces the precision of the simulation, which itself might cause problems if taken too far, or if the client and server simulations are running at significantly different rates.
[src:client-side-prediction/netcode] Because of limitations in the amount of available bandwidth and the CPU time that's taken by network communication, some games prioritize certain vital communications while limiting the frequency and priority of less important information.
[src:client-side-prediction/netcode] As with tickrate, this effectively increases synchronization latency.
[src:client-side-prediction/netcode] Game engines may limit the number of times that updates (of a simulation) are sent to a particular client and/or particular objects in the game's world in addition to reducing the precision of some values sent over the network to help with bandwidth use.
[src:client-side-prediction/netcode] This lack of precision may in some instances be noticeable.
[src:client-side-prediction/netcode] Various simulation synchronization errors between machines can also fall under the "netcode issues" blanket.
[src:client-side-prediction/netcode] These may include bugs which cause the simulation to proceed differently on one machine than on another, or which cause some things to not be communicated when the user perceives that they ought to be.
[src:client-side-prediction/netcode] A game's choice of transport layer protocol (and its management and coding) can also affect perceived networking issues.
[src:client-side-prediction/netcode] If a game uses Transmission Control Protocol (TCP), there will be increased latency between players.
[src:client-side-prediction/netcode] This protocol is based on the connection between two machines, in which they can exchange data and read it.
[src:client-side-prediction/netcode] These types of connections are very reliable, stable, ordered and easy to implement.
[src:client-side-prediction/netcode] This type of protocol also tends to respond very slowly whenever they lose a packet, or when packets arrive in an incorrect order or duplicated, which can be very detrimental to a real-time online game (this protocol was not designed for this type of software).
[src:client-side-prediction/netcode] If the game instead uses a User Datagram Protocol (UDP), the connection between machines will be very fast, because instead of establishing a connection between them the data will be sent and received directly.
